People joke about how Dubai seems so "Indian" (in the pejorative sense, in spite of my Hinduphilia), but the official monetary system in the UAE (or, as it was called at the time, the "Trucial Coast") was called the "Gulf rupee" until the 1960s. It was pegged to the Indian rupee.

The British saw much of the Arab world as part of India. It's all "Orient" to them. Parts of Yemen (Aden) under the British Protectorate of South Arabia were literally considered a part of India during the Bombay Presidency. Dubai is part of "Greater India", as is also Singapore.

The UAE itself is a fascinating country because it is one "democratic federation" consisting of seven absolute monarchies. Abu Dhabi the Emirate takes most space, Dubai is the second largest, then there are five more in the East most people have not heard much about. Mysterious.
India is as big as the rest of the world and any single philosophical or religious debate we have has been discussed for centuries by Hindu philosophers thousands of years ago

It's a small institution and a niche field, I guess they all knew each other and it was "pro forma" because they were going to make him a PhD no matter what, a lot of dissertations even in medicine are abominably bad and no one cares because it doesn't really change anything

Also oil makes less than 1% of Dubai's GDP. Abu Dhabi has all the oil, a different Emirate. The Port of Jebel Ali in Dubai is the largest shipping port in the Middle East. Dubai is the gateway to the rest of the "Middle East". It's an anonymous hotel-state, a mirror of the world.
